http://www.tovima.gr/science/article/?aid=436005</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2011</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>DDF8B279-20F7-49F4-8099-1C22E3A14641</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>We published the first analysis of gene expression during neurogenic placode development in a basal ray-finned fish, the North American paddlefish (Polyodon spathula), including the identification of Sox3 as the first published molecular marker for electrosensory ampullary organs in ray-finned fish. We also published the first fate-mapping data from any electroreceptive ray-finned fish, again the paddlefish Polyodon spathula, using focal DiI labelling to demonstrate a lateral line placodal origin for ampullary organs (and neuromasts) in this species. Taken together with previous data showing that ampullary organs in the axolotl (a representative of the lobe-finned fish clade) are lateral line placode-derived, our results showed that ampullary organs are ancestrally lateral line placode-derived in bony fishes. 

This work was widely publicised, e.g.:
http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sciencetech/article-2048216/Humans-descended-animal-sixth-sense.html

http://palaeoblog.blogspot.co.uk/2011/10/humans-descended-from-ancestor-with.html

http://www.futura-sciences.com/fr/news/t/zoologie/d/lelectroreception-le-sixieme-sens-de-notre-ancetre_33986/

http://www.tovima.gr/science/article/?aid=436005

We also published Eya4 expression during otic and lateral line placode development in the axolotl: together with our previous work in paddlefish and shark, this confirms that Eya4 is a conserved marker for lateral line placodes and their derivatives in all jawed vertebrates.

We also published the first fate map of the neurogenic placodes in lampreys (generated using focal DiI labelling; this was a collaboration with Marianne Bronner, Caltech).

Work funded by this grant also contributed to a paper showing that ampullary organs in the skate (a cartilaginous fish) are lateral line placode-derived. In conjunction with our work on paddlefish, this showed that ampullary organs are ancestrally lateral line placode-derived in all jawed vertebrates.

Work funded by this grant also contributed to a paper describing the developmental evidence for serial homology of the vertebrate jaw and gill arch skeleton, and to another paper on the evolution of the vertebrate cerebellum.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We have created useful tools for the community by cloning a large number of cDNA fragments from various vertebrate species, which have been (or will be, upon publication) deposited in public databases.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>EA2EA70C-EC83-459D-9470-75024459429D</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/3A9049D1-7597-4D86-84B1-44E10E46CCDA"><gtr:id>3A9049D1-7597-4D86-84B1-44E10E46CCDA</gtr:id><gtr:title>A timeline of pharyngeal endoskeletal condensation and differentiation in the shark, Scyliorhinus canicula, and the paddlefish, Polyodon spathula.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Zeitschrift fur angewandte Ichthyologie = Journal of applied ichthyology</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/1ff98f8d977df9169e0acf0f23c55cfe"><gtr:id>1ff98f8d977df9169e0acf0f23c55cfe</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Gillis JA</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:issn>0175-8659</gtr:issn></gtr:publication><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/504A4BE2-3D80-4492-8859-67BF4077E005"><gtr:id>504A4BE2-3D80-4492-8859-67BF4077E005</gtr:id><gtr:title>Molecular analysis of neurogenic placode development in a basal ray-finned fish.</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Genesis (New York, N.Y. : 2000)</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:a